China (cid:1) 2019 Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group ABSTRACT Six julichrome derivatives including a new monomeric julichrome named as julichrome Q10 (1), and previous reported julichrome Q6 (2), julichrome Q6.6 (4), julichrome Q3.5 (5), julichrome Q5.6 (6), julichrome Q2.3 (7), along with a diketopiperazine gliotoxin (3) were isolated from a soil derived strain Streptomyces sp. The struc- tures of these compounds were identified by HR-ESI-MS, UV, IR and NMR methods. The isolated compounds were tested for their in vitro cytotoxicity against human hepatocarcinoma HepG-2 and SMMC-7721 cell lines, human breast cancer MCF-7 and MDA-MB- 231 cell lines, and human normal heptical LO2 cell line. Gliotoxin (3) showed the most cytotoxic activity against the tested tumor ranging from 0.11 to 1.45 lM. cell Julichrome Q6.6 (4) displayed selective cytotoxic activity against SMMC-7721, MCF-7 and MDA-MB-231 cell lines. and 12T061A (Komoda et al. 2016), and twenty julichrome dimers have been identified from terrestrial Streptomyces sp. (Tsuji 1968; Tsuji and Nagashim 1968; Tsuji and Nagashima 1969a, 1969b; Tsuji et al. 1969; Tsuji and Nagashima 1970, 1971). The bio- synthetic investigations indicated that the monomers composing of julichromes are derived from a nonaketidic precursor in bacteria. Two of these monomers will regiose- lectively couple to provide the corresponding julichrome dimer via oxidative phenol coupling within each organism (Pr€ag et al. 2014). Julichrome derivatives displayed broad-spectrum biological activity in antimicrobial property, and showed moderate cytotoxic activity against a range of human tumor cell lines (Shaaban et al. 2007; Komoda et al. 2016). In addition, it has potential application value in agricultural anti- biotics as an inhibitor of plant transformation (Kanzaki et al. 1993).

Strain Streptomyces sp. NH1835 was isolated from soil samples at the suburb of Wanning, Hainan province, China. Its 16S rRNA nucleotide sequence shared 100% simi- larity with the Streptomyces phaeopureus in GenBank. The EtOAc extract of culture medium of Streptomyces sp. NH1835 displayed several yellow spots in TLC analysis presumably presented by aromatic polyketides. Subsequent large scale fermentation and chromatography isolation led to the identifi- cation of seven yellow-powder compounds inclunding six julichrome derivative juli- chrome Q10 (1), julichrome Q6 (2), julichrome Q6.6 (4), julichrome Q3.5 (5), julichrome Q5.6 (6) and julichrome Q2.3 (7), along with a diketopiperazine gliotoxin (3) (Figure 1). Compound 1 was identified as a new julichrome monomer. According to literature review, compound 5 showed a moderate and rather unselective cytotoxic activity against a range of human tumor cell lines with a mean IC50 of 6.3 mM (Shaaban et al. 2007). Compound 3, an epidithiodioxopiperazine mycotoxin, is a secondary metabolite produced by Aspergillus fumigatus, Gliocladium fimbriatum, and several other fungal It species (Vigushin et al. 2004). We isolated it from Streptomyces for the first time. modulates the immune response and induces apoptosis in different cell types (Scharf et al. 2012). In a 48-h sulforhodamine B assay, Compound 3 inhibited proliferation of six breast cancer cell lines with IC50 values ranging from 38 to 985 nM (Vigushin et al. The inhibitory effect of compound 3 on human breast cancer MCF-7 and MDA-MB-231 cell lines has been reported in the literature (Vigushin et al. 2004) and the rest were first reported.

Compound 1 was isolated as a yellow powder. Those measurements suggested that 1 have a similar chemical structure to juli- chrome Q6 (Shaaban et al. 2007; Pr€ag et al. 2014) except that the 1H NMR spectrum of compound 1 has only two methyl signal, the 13C NMR spectrum has five carbon sig- nals in the range of dC 20–80. The HMBC correlations from H-13 to C-2, C-3 and C-4, H-12 to C-11 indicated two of the methyl groups are connected to C-3 and C-11; the correlations from H-4 to C-11, C-4a, C-10, C-9a and C-3 indicated C-11 is connected to C-4. the correlations from H-2 to C-1, C-3 and C-13 indicated the C-2 is connected to C-1 and C-3. Combine the HMBC correlations from H-10 to C-4, C-9a and C-8a, H-5 to C-10 and C-7, H-6 to C-8, H-7 to C-8a and 1H-1H COSY correlations of H-5/H-6/H-7 indi- cated the naphthalene system, which is attached to a cyclohexanone ring at C-4a and C-9a. The cyclohexanone ring is substituted with a methyl group and a hydroxyl group at C-3. The position at C-4 was also substituted with an acetyl moiety. Therefore, the planar structure of 1 was established. The relative stereochemistry of 1 was deduced by a differential NOE experiment. The structures of 2–7 were respectively identified as julichrome Q6 (2) (Shaaban et al. 2007; Pr€ag et al. 2014), gliotoxin (3) (Pena et al. 2015), julichrome Q6.6 (4) (Tsuji and Nagashima 1971), julichrome Q5.6 (6) (Tsuji and Nagashima 1971) and julichrome Q2.3 (7) (Tsuji and Nagashima 1969a) by comparison of their HR-ESI-MS, 1H and 13C NMR data with those reported in literature. All isolated compounds (1–7) were evaluated for their activity in inhibiting the pro- liferation of human tumour HepG-2, SMMC-7721, MCF-7, MDA-MB-231 cells, and human normal heptical LO2 cell by MTT assay. Doxorubicin (Tacar et al. 2013) was used as a positive control. Compounds 3 and 4 had antiproliferative activity against the five tested cell lines with IC50 values from 0.11 to 15.84 lM. It seemed that com- pound 3 showed stronger activity than the positive control drug (Doxorubicin) to SMMC-7721, MCF-7 and MDA-MB-231 cells. Moreover, the compound 4 is more sensi- tive to MCF-7 cell (IC50: 0.99lM) and MDA-MB-231 cell (IC50: 0.92lM) than to other three cells. Unfortunately, the new compound julichrome Q10 (1), and previous reported julichrome Q6 (2), julichrome Q6.6 (4), julichrome Q3.5 (5), julichrome Q5.6 (6) and julichrome Q2.3 (7) displayed no activity to tumour cell lines at the concentrations of 20 lM. 3.2. Microorganism and fermentation The strain NH1835 was isolated using the standard dilution coating plate method from soil samples at the suburb of Wanning, Hainan province, China, in February 2018. The taxonomic identity of strain NH1835 was determined by 16S rRNA analysis. Gauze’s medium No.1 containing soluble starch 2.0%, KNO3 0.1%, K2HPO4 0.05%, MgSO4(cid:4)7H2O 0.05%, FeSO4(cid:4)7H2O 0.01% and agar 2.0%, pH 7.4 was used as culture media with potassium dichromate (6.0 mg/L) and nalidixic acid (20.0 mg/L). This strain was picked after 7 days with inoculating ring to Gause’s agar plates and was main- tained at 32 (cid:5)C. The well-developed colonies of seed medium were used for the inoculation of 30 L Gauze’s medium No.1 by dilution-plate coating method and incubated at 32 (cid:5)C incu- bator for 9 days. 3.3. Extraction and isolation

The final 30 L of solid medium from the 900 plates were cut into small pieces and extracted with EtOAc three times. The EtOAc extract was evaporated under reduced pressure at 32 (cid:5)C to afford 8.6 g crude extracts. The crude extract was subjected to sil- ica gel (300–400 mesh) CC eluted with a mixture of n-hexane-acetone (20:1, 10:1, 5:1, 2:1 and 1:1, v/v) to yield five fractions. Fr.3 (n-hexane-acetone 5:1, 510.0 mg) was puri- fied by semi-preparative HPLC using a YMC Triart C18 column (20 (cid:3) 250 mm) with a lin- ear gradient of 10–90% CH3CN in H2O over 60 min at flow rate of 20.0 mL/min and detected with 254 nm UV detection to yield 2 (10.0 mg), 1 (2.0 mg) and 3 (3.0 mg) at retention time of 23.5 min, 31.0 min and 43.5 min, respectively. Fr.4 (n-hexane-acetone 2:1,440.0 mg) and fraction Fr.5 (n-hexane-acetone 1:1,980.0 mg) were combined and purified by semi-preparative HPLC using the same condition as before except that elu- tion system becomes a linear gradient of 53-100% CH3CN in H2O to yield 4 (87.0 mg), 5 (4.2 mg), 6 (7.9 mg) and 7 (3.0 mg) at retention time of 30.5 min, 31.5 min, 33.0 min and 44.0 min, respectively.

NH 1835. Among the tested compounds, gliotoxin and julichrome Q6.6 exhibited activity in inhibiting the proliferation of five tested HepG-2, SMMC-7721, MCF-7, MDA-MB-231 and LO2 cell lines. Especially, gliotoxin showed relatively stronger effect on SMMC-7721 and MDA- MB-231 cell lines with IC50 value of 0.11 lM, 0.26 lM, which were lower than positive control drug (Doxorubicin).
